<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="<%= I18n.locale %>">
  <head>
    <meta charset="utf-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">
    <%# We now ship a designed dark variant rather than forcing light: declaring
        BOTH schemes tells WebKit-based clients (Apple Mail, new Outlook for Mac,
        iOS Mail) to apply the @media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) rules below
        instead of running their own blunt auto-darkening, which muddied the cream
        ground into olive. Clients that ignore the query just render the light
        inline styles — the existing cream look, unchanged. %>
    <meta name="color-scheme" content="light dark">
    <meta name="supported-color-schemes" content="light dark">
    <%# Dark theme, mirroring the app's own dark palette (#17131a plum ground,
        #d4ced3 warm off-white text, #38c08a green). The body is styled inline for
        the light/default render and for clients that strip <style>; these rules
        carry !important because a stylesheet !important is the ONE thing that
        beats an inline style in the cascade — that's what lets a single <style>
        block re-skin a fully inline-styled email. Each class maps one role:
          u-ground   outer ground + body          u-rule        hairline (header/footer/card)
          u-card     the floating card            u-rule-soft   between-row hairline
          u-text     primary foreground           u-rule-strong date underline
          u-muted    secondary text               u-accent      green (links, ↗, footer)
          u-btn      primary CTA                  u-warn        cancelled flag
        The logo is swapped (not recoloured): u-logo-light hides / u-logo-dark
        shows, so the mark's own ground matches whichever card it sits on. %>
    <style>
      @media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) {
        body, .u-ground { background:#100d13 !important; }
        body { color:#d4ced3 !important; }
        .u-card { background:#17131a !important; border-color:#34303a !important; }
        .u-text { color:#d4ced3 !important; }
        .u-muted { color:#968d97 !important; }
        .u-rule { border-color:#34303a !important; }
        .u-rule-soft { border-color:#2a262f !important; }
        .u-rule-strong { border-color:#565060 !important; }
        .u-accent { color:#38c08a !important; }
        .u-warn { color:#f0837a !important; }
        .u-btn { background:#38c08a !important; color:#17131a !important; border-color:#38c08a !important; }
        .u-logo-light { display:none !important; width:0 !important; height:0 !important; max-height:0 !important; overflow:hidden !important; }
        .u-logo-dark { display:inline-block !important; width:36px !important; height:36px !important; max-height:none !important; overflow:visible !important; }
      }

      <%# Outlook.com / Outlook-on-the-web / Windows "new Outlook" dark mode: these
          do NOT honor prefers-color-scheme — they rewrite colors in place and tag
          each touched element with data-ogsc (overrode text color) / data-ogsb
          (overrode background). Re-asserting our palette on those attributed
          elements stops the blunt rewrite from muddying the design. Outlook only
          supports the solo ([attr]) and element (E[attr]) attribute-selector
          forms — NOT compound (.class[attr]) — so we either match the element
          itself (body[data-ogsb]) or descend from an attributed ANCESTOR
          ([data-ogsb] .u-card). body has no attributed ancestor, so it must be the
          element form. (Classic Word-engine Outlook for Windows and Outlook for
          Mac don't use these attributes at all — the data-URI background tiles
          above are what protect the grounds there.) %>
      body[data-ogsb], .u-ground[data-ogsb], [data-ogsb] .u-ground { background:#100d13 !important; }
      body[data-ogsc] { color:#d4ced3 !important; }
      [data-ogsb] .u-card, .u-card[data-ogsb] { background:#17131a !important; }
      [data-ogsc] .u-card { border-color:#34303a !important; }
      [data-ogsc] .u-text { color:#d4ced3 !important; }
      [data-ogsc] .u-muted { color:#968d97 !important; }
      [data-ogsc] .u-rule { border-color:#34303a !important; }
      [data-ogsc] .u-rule-soft { border-color:#2a262f !important; }
      [data-ogsc] .u-rule-strong { border-color:#565060 !important; }
      [data-ogsc] .u-accent { color:#38c08a !important; }
      [data-ogsc] .u-warn { color:#f0837a !important; }
      [data-ogsb] .u-btn { background:#38c08a !important; }
      [data-ogsc] .u-btn { color:#17131a !important; border-color:#38c08a !important; }
    </style>
  </head>
  <%# Mirrors the app's light theme: Space Mono (monospace identity, with a robust
      system-mono fallback since email clients can't be trusted to load a web font),
      cream ground, near-black text. Sharp corners + neutral hairlines + green-only-
      for-interaction are carried by the inline styles in the digest body; the dark
      counterparts live in the <style> block above. %>
  <body style="margin:0; padding:0; background:#e8e1cd; -webkit-font-smoothing:antialiased; font-family:'Space Mono', ui-monospace, 'SF Mono', 'Cascadia Mono', 'Roboto Mono', Menlo, Consolas, monospace; color:#1d1620;">
    <%= yield %>
  </body>
</html>
